  "local_port": 36242,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much money in charitable donations can a person deduct from his/her taxes before being taxed on his/her donations in the US?",
  "response": "In the United States, charitable donations can be tax-deductible, but the extent to which you can deduct them depends on several factors, including your adjusted gross income (AGI) and the type of organization you're donating to.\n\n1. **AGI Limits:**\n   - For cash donations to public charities (like 501(c)(3) organizations), generally, you can deduct up to 60% of your AGI.\n   - For donations of non-cash assets (such as stocks or property), the limit is typically 30% of your AGI.\n   - For donations to private foundations or other types of organizations, the limits may be lower, often 30% for cash and 20% for non-cash assets.\n\n2. **Carryover Provisions:**\n   - If your charitable contributions exceed these AGI limits in a given year, you can carry over the excess amount and deduct it in future tax years, for up to five years.\n\n3. **Itemizing Deductions:**\n   - To claim a tax deduction for charitable donations, you must itemize your deductions on your tax return. If you take the standard deduction, you cannot deduct charitable contributions.\n\n4. **Documentation Requirements:**\n   - You must have proper documentation for your donations, such as receipts or acknowledgments from the charitable organizations, especially for donations above $250.\n\n5. **Special Considerations:**\n   - In some years, special provisions may temporarily increase the deduction limits. For example, during the COVID-19 pandemic, taxpayers were allowed to deduct up to 100% of their AGI for cash donations to public charities in 2020 and 2021.\n\nAlways consult with a tax professional or refer to the latest IRS guidelines to ensure you are complying with current tax laws and maximizing your deductions.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
